theorem
fixes p q :: real
assumes h0 : "(q + 4) * (p + 3) - (q + 2) * (p + 1) = 44"
shows  "p + q = 17"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Find $p+q$, given that $(q+4)(p+3)-(q+2)(p+1)=44$. The final Answer is 17
 ### Proof
 We multiply the binomials: \begin{align} (q+4)(p+3)-(q+2)(p+1)&=44\\ q(p+3)+4(p+3)-(q(p+1)+2(p+1))&=44\\ pq+3q+4p+12-(pq+q+2p+2)&=44\\ 2q+2p+10&=44\\ 2q+2p&=34\\ q+p&=\boxed{17}\\ \end{align}
 *)

theorem
fixes p q :: real
assumes h0 : "(q + 4) * (p + 3) - (q + 2) * (p + 1) = 44"
shows  "p + q = 17"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
